rs examine phylogenetic relationships between shorebirds and other birds, and cover shorebird morphology, anatomy, and physiology. A section on breeding biology looks in detail at their reproductive biology. Because shorebirds spend much of their time away from breeding areas, a substantial section on non-breeding biology covers migration, foraging ecology, and social behavior. The text also covers shorebird demography, population size, and management issues related to habitat, predators, and human disturbances. Throughout, it emphasizes applying scientific knowledge to the conservation of shorebird populations, many of which are unfortunately in decline.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aShore birdsxConservation. 0aShore birds. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Zoology / General.2bisacsh  aanimal population.  aanimals.  aavian group.  aavian.  abiology.  abirds.  abreeding areas.  abreeding biology.  abreeding.  aconservation.  aearth sciences.  aecology.  aenvironment.  aenvironmentalism.  aestuaries.  aforaging.  afreshwater.  ahabitat.  alife sciences.  amigration.  anature.  anonfiction.  aornithology.  apredators.  areproductive biology.  ascience.  ashorebirds.  asocial behavior.  awetlands.  awildlife.  azoology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026640740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094796240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520947962423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520947962/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY